[00:08.78]Of all the changes that have taken place in English-language newspapers during the past quarter-century,
[00:15.56]perhaps the most far-reaching has been the inexorable decline
[00:21.45]in the scope and seriousness of their arts coverage.
[00:29.00]It is difficult to the point of impossibility for the average reader
[00:34.65]under the age of forty to imagine a time
[00:37.36]when high-quality arts criticism could be found in most big-city newspapers.
[00:43.30]Yet a considerable number of the most significant collections of criticism published
[00:49.58]in the 20th century consisted in large part of newspaper reviews.
[00:55.22]To read such books today is to marvel at the fact that
[00:59.66]their learned contents were once deemed suitable for publication in general-circulation dailies.
[01:08.94]We are even farther removed from the unfocused newspaper reviews published in England
[01:15.03]between the turn of the 20th century and the eve of World War ¢ò,
[01:22.17]at a time when newsprint was dirt-cheap and stylish arts criticism
[01:28.25]was considered an ornament to the publications in which it appeared.
[01:33.98]In those far-off days, it was taken for granted that the critics of major papers would write in detail
[01:42.91]and at length about the events they covered.
[01:46.01]Theirs was a serious business, and even those reviewers who wore their learning lightly,
[01:52.60]like George Bernard Shaw and Ernest Newman,
[01:56.20]could be trusted to know what they were about.
[02:00.52]These men believed in journalism as a calling,
[02:04.86]and were proud to be published in the daily press.
